[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27916] [2812007] [debug] Unknown: List::Util
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27920] [2812007] [debug] Token: List::Util. Extras:
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27922] [2812007] [debug] 	- use List::Util 'any' or, better, 'first' (but don't use first() for finding 0 or undef!)
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27923] [2812007] [debug] 	- And then 1 of
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27925] [2812007] [debug] 	- if(any { $_ eq $thing } @values) ...
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27926] [2812007] [debug] 	- if(any { $_ == $thing } @values) ...
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27928] [2812007] [debug] 	- It's not limited to just string or number comparison of course; you can
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27929] [2812007] [debug] 	put any arbitrary code in there. if(any { $_->is_close_to(123.45) } @values) ...
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27931] [2812007] [debug] 	- Or
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27932] [2812007] [debug] 	- If you don't like the XSUB call overhead of List::Util::any, there's
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27934] [2812007] [debug] 	another (non-core) CPAN module List::Keywords which implements many of
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27935] [2812007] [debug] 	the same utilities as real keywords with real opcodes, so they run
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27937] [2812007] [debug] 	faster.
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27938] [2812007] [debug] 	- use List::Keywords 'any';
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27939] [2812007] [debug] 	- if(any { $_ eq $thing } @values) ...
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27941] [2812007] [debug] 	- Or
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.27942] [2812007] [debug] 	- if (grep { $_ eq $myval } @arr)
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.28094] [2812007] [debug] Unknown: List::UtilsBy
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.28097] [2812007] [debug] Token: List::UtilsBy. Extras:
[2026-05-28 14:49:47.28099] [2812007] [debug] 	- Amazing!
