[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58313] [2812007] [debug] 	<pre>
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58314] [2812007] [debug] 	Note: GraphViz2::DBI includes db.schema.pl, which creates an SVG image of a schema
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58316] [2812007] [debug] 	- To run it you need to set three environment variables as below
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58317] [2812007] [debug] 	- dbi.schema.pl takes an option parameter of image type, which defaults to svg
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58319] [2812007] [debug] 	- Edit the code if you wish to change the output dir's name
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58320] [2812007] [debug] 	- The last line, the copy, is for my setup. $DR points to a RAM disk. Debian automatically creates a RAM disk, so I configure the free web server Engine X, aka nginx, to use it. See my other TiddlyWiki, Debian.Wiki.html, for details about nginx
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58322] [2812007] [debug] 	- And yes, you can use empty strings for the username and password
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58323] [2812007] [debug] 	- Lastly, $ is just the command line prompt
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58325] [2812007] [debug] 	$ DBI_DSN=dbi:SQLite:dbname=data/levies.sqlite
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58326] [2812007] [debug] 	$ DBI_USER=local
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58327] [2812007] [debug] 	$ DBI_PASS=local
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58329] [2812007] [debug] 	$ export DBI_DSN DBI_USER DBI_PASS
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58330] [2812007] [debug] 	$ mkdir html
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58331] [2812007] [debug] 	$ dbi.schema.pl (my version)
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58333] [2812007] [debug] 	$ cp html/dbi.schema.svg $DR/levy.schema.svg
[2026-05-28 14:49:48.58334] [2812007] [debug] 	</pre>
